@Node "Starting from Workbench" "pro.guide/Starting from Workbench"

Starting from Workbench
-----------------------

    The easiest way to run ASX is from the Workbench.  A double-click
on its icon loads the program.  The @{b}ENV:asx.prefs@{ub} configuration file
will be loaded and processed immediately, if not otherwise desired (see
the @{b}LOCALPREFS@{ub} tooltype below).  The configuration file is an ASCII text
that can be edited using a texteditor if needed.

    If ASX is already running and you invoke it again, it will open the
user interface window of the already running version.

    When ASX is started from the WorkBench, the following tooltypes are
recognized:
@{b}CX_PRIORITY=@{i}n@{ui}@{ub}
     Set priority of the commodity to @{i}n@{ui}.  By default, ASX uses a
     priority of 0.

@{b}CX_POPKEY=@{i}hotkey@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype allows you to specify the hotkey for ASX to @{i}hotkey@{ui}.
     @{i}Hotkey@{ui} must be a valid key sequence for a hotkey.  If you enter an
     incorrect description, a message will be displayed or a requester
     is opened to inform you.  (The hotkey format is described in the
     `AmigaDOS 2.0 manual').  By default, @{b}lcommand help@{ub} is used as
     hotkey.

     If you have defined a hotkey, ASX can be called up at any time by
     pressing that key sequence.

@{b}CX_POPUP=@{i}YES|NO@{ui}@{ub}
     This options allows you to select whether the user interface window
     of ASX is opened at startup or not.  @{i}YES@{ui} must be used to open the
     user interface window.  By default, ASX does not open the window.

@{b}APPICON@{ub}
     If this tooltype is selected, ASX displays an AppIcon on the
     workbench screen.  See @{"The AppIcon" Link "The AppIcon"}.

@{b}ICONX=@{i}x@{ui}@{ub}
@{b}ICONY=@{i}y@{ui}@{ub}
     These tooltypes allow you to specify the position of the AppIcon
     on the WorkBench screen relative to the top left edge.  The @{i}x@{ui} and
     @{i}y@{ui} coordinates are integer values that describe the top left
     position.

     Normally, the AppIcon will be positioned automatically in an
     appropriate position on the screen, but you may sometimes want to
     override this with your own preferred coordinates.

@{b}NOLIBRARY@{ub}
     If this tooltype is selected, ASX will not add the @{b}asx.library@{ub} to
     the system.  (See @{"The asx.library" Link "The asx.library"}).  By default, the library is
     installed.

@{b}ASMPATH=@{i}assembler@{ui}@{ub}
     Using this tooltype you can specify the location and the name of
     ProAsm.  @{i}assembler@{ui} describes the path and filename of the ProAsm
     assembler.  By default ASX searches the assembler as @{b}pro@{ub} in the
     following locations: @{b}asm:@{ub} and the current directory.

@{b}SWAP@{ub}
     This tooltype tells ASX to load ProAsm each time when used.  By
     default, the assembler is once loaded residently.  Loading the
     assembler residently can be useful on disk based systems.  This
     tooltype is also recommended on systems with little memory.

@{b}ERRFILE=@{i}filename@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype defines the name of the error file to @{i}filename@{ui} that
     is automatically used for all assembly task started by ASX (via
     ARexx and asx.library).

@{b}HEADERFILE=@{i}filename@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype defines the header @{i}filename@{ui} that is automatically
     used for all assembly task started by ASX (via ARexx and
     asx.library).

@{b}CONFIGFILE=@{i}filename@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype defines the configuration @{i}filename@{ui} that is
     automatically used for all assembly task started by ASX (via ARexx
     and asx.library).

@{b}NOREQ@{ub}
     If this tooltype is selected, ASX will not open any message
     requesters.  This can be useful if you do not want to be
     interrupted by these requesters.  But note that also all error
     message reported by ASX will be suppressed silently.

@{b}NORASTER@{ub}
     To get a stronger 3D-look, ASX fills the background of all its
     windows with a pattern.  If you do not want to have this pattern
     as background, you can unselect this tooltype and it will be
     written automatically to the settings file when you save settings.
     By default, a rastered background is displayed.

@{b}LOCALPREFS=@{i}filename@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype tells ASX to use the file @{i}filename@{ui} as configuration
     file, instead of the default configuration file named
     @{b}ENV:asx.prefs@{ub}.

@{b}NOMASTER@{ub}
     This tooltype can be used to forbid the source manager.  By
     default, the source manager is enabled.

@{b}AREXXSCRIPT=@{i}filename@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype allows you to specify the ARexx script that is
     executed when an entry in the source manager is selected.
     @{i}Filename@{ui} is the complete name and path of the ARexx script.
     By default, @{b}rexx:pro/sourcemanager.rexx@{ub} is used.

@{b}SMHOTKEY=@{i}hotkey@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype allows you to specify the hotkey for the source
     manager to @{i}hotkey@{ui}.  @{i}Hotkey@{ui} must be a valid key sequence for a
     hotkey.  If you enter an incorrect description, a message will be
     displayed or a requester is opened to inform you.  (The hotkey
     format is described in the `AmigaDOS 2.0 manual').  By default,
     @{b}lcommand shift help@{ub} is used as hotkey.

     If you have defined a hotkey, the source manager can be called up
     at any time by pressing that key sequence.

@{b}SMPUBSCREEN=@{i}screenname@{ui}@{ub}
     This tooltype can be used to specify the public screen the source
     manager should be opened on.  @{i}Screenname@{ui} is the name of the
     desired public screen.  By default, the source manager opens its
     window on the front public screen.

@{b}NOFALLBACK@{ub}
     This tooltype forbids the source manager window to open its window
     on the default public screen if the explicitly specified public
     screen is not available.  By default, the source manager does
     "fall back".


@EndNode

